commit.message: Compatibility fix for recent version of tensorflow

Fix format detection with Python 2

Format detection didn't work correctly with Python 2 because with the
new format data, `weights[i][0][0][0][0]` was an instance of
`numpy.unicode_`, which is not a subclass of `str`. The check worked
fine with Python 3, where the value was an instance of `numpy.str_`,
which is a subclass of `str`.

This patch changes the way we detect the data format so it works on both
Python 2 and Python 3.

Make VGG code compatible with old/new format data

Commit 6197b175bf1f15d757b1d92f6747c5faa06c1ed8 noted that the VGG model
data was available in multiple formats. The code was only compatible
with the old format, so the README was updated to include a link to the
old format data. This was a source of confusion, because people didn't
download the model using the link from the README and ended up with the
new-format data, which caused the program to crash. Later, a more
descriptive error message was added, but this continued to be a source
of confusion.

This patch updates the VGG data loading code to be compatible with both
old and new data formats.

Allow curly brace formatting, startup checks, code style

Allow '{}'-formatting for `checkpoint_output`. Default CLI is unchanged.

Add startup options consistency check for `checkpoint_iterations` and
`checkpoint_output. Make sure we have both of them set. There has been
inconsistent behavior before: when `checkpoint_iterations` was not set, the
code still wrote `out_<last-iter>.png` in addition to `out.png`

Misc code style changes (mostly line width).

Add write and plot options for progress data (loss values)

Add --progress-write and --progress-plot to save and/or plot loss values at
every print_iterations step.

For that, we need to modify the behavior of the stylize() function. This
function now yields tuples (iteration, image, loss_vals) at *every* iteration,
not every checkpoint_iterations and at the last step as before. Also, stylize()
does not set `iteration` to None at the last step. `image` and `loss_vals` are
None by default. Each `checkpoint_iterations`, `image` is not None. Each
`print_iterations`, `loss_vals` is not None, i.e we can save images and
store the loss at different frequencies.

`loss_vals` is a dict with loss values for the current iteration, e.g.
``{'content': 1.23, 'style': 4.56, 'tv': 7.89, 'total': 13.68}``.

neural_style.py was adapted accordingly. The default CLI behavior of
neural_style.py is unchanged.

commit.message:
Add check to verify that output file is writable

This helps avoid situations where the optimization runs for a long time
and the results are lost, e.g. because of a typo like setting `--output
foo.jgp`.
Add elapsed and remaining time to output
Add warning about using wrong VGG19 data
